07567nam a22011535i 9783110652246DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2019955042  a97831106522467 a10.1515/97831106522462doi  a(DE-B1597)514709  a(OCoLC)1149506065  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aP301.5.I73bD58 2020 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04aThe Diversity of Irony /ced. by Angeliki Athanasiadou, Herbert L. Colston. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (VIII, 307 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCognitive Linguistics Research [CLR] ;v6500tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tIntroduction. On the diversity of irony -- tPart I: Diversity across figures -- tUniting irony, hyperbole and metaphor in an affect-centred, pretence-based framework -- tHow defaultness affects text production: Resonating with default interpretations of negative sarcasm -- tIrony in constructions -- tHyperbolic Figures -- tDenying the salient contrast. Speaker’s attitude in hyperbole -- tPart II: Diversity across languages -- tThai irony as an indirect relational tool to save face in social interactions -- tEngland is an appendix; Corrupt officials are like hairs on a nation’s arm: Sarcasm, irony and self-irony in figurative political discourse -- tGrammatical emphasis and irony in Spanish -- tPart III: Diversity across media -- tEye-rolling, irony and embodiment -- tExperimental investigations of irony as a viewpoint phenomenon -- tFaces of sarcasm. Exploring raised eyebrows with sarcasm in French political debates -- tA pilot study on the diversity in irony production and irony perception -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough the figure of irony has enjoyed extensive attention through important contributions to the diverse literatures addressing figurative thought and language, it still remains relatively in the background compared to other figures such as metaphor and metonymy. The present volume, together with a 2017 collection by Angeliki Athanasiadou and Herbert L. Colston, aims to the further exploration of verbal and situational irony, its gestural accompaniments, its comprehension and interpretation, its constructional diversity and its cooperation with other figures such as metaphor and hyperbole. The present volume is a highly interesting collection of chapters dealing with both theoretical investigations and descriptive applications of a central figure pervading human thought and language. Its aim is to draw more attention to irony’s diversity and its concomitant connections to other aspects of figurativeness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aIrony. 4aDiversität. 4aIronie. 4aMulitmodalität. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aFigurative Language.  aHyperbole.  aIrony.  aMultimodal.1 aAthanasiadou, Angeliki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAthanasiadou, Angeliki, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBarnden, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBecker, Israela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColston, Herbert L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColston, Herbert L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDerek Wong, Sing Tsun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEscandell-Vidal, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiora, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGivoni, Shir, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc